   <h1>Re: [VB] Tranny is Toast! Help! (looong)</h1>
   <b>Derrick Pacheco &lt;DerrickP_at_auctionweb_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2000-08-11 16:49:28+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Excellent...just what I wanted to hear :)  I have the Bently, just not in
front of me (i'm at work) but i'll take a look at it.  So in order to
replace it, I have to drop the engine and slide the trans out a little to do
so, right? The trans is also whining quite a bit, and now in fourth, makes
sort of a bubbling/gurgling sound.  Needs a rebuild? Back to my other
question. What trans do I get? Will a new Rancho from Ronnie solve this? I
know I can't just shove a new one in there and drive off...so what is
involved on my end in terms of getting the old one out and the new one in?
Thanks.

on 8/11/00 9:38 AM, Thom Fitzpatrick at thom_at_calweb_dot_com wrote:

> Do you have one of the repair manuals?
> 
> The front mount is a rubber-centered, sorta rectangualr thing.  The
> transmission bolts to it, then it bolts to the body.  The rubber and
> adhesive deteriorate over time, and it comes unglued.   When it does,
> the weight of the engine on the transmission causes the front of the
> transmission to lift.  This puts strain on the coupler, and nose cone.
> If left too long, it will crack the nose cone, bend the shift rod,
> and possibly damage the shift selector.
> 
> To replace it, you will need to slide the transmission back about 3"
> or so.  Ideally, you should replace the coupler, front mount, and the
> two rear mounts all at the same time.  You could also do the axle boots
> while you're at it.  Yes, it's a solid afternoon of greasy work, but
> you won't have to worry about this stuff for a while!
> 
> Derrick Pacheco wrote:
>> That would make me pretty happy! If a $15 part will fix it great!! So today
>> i'll crawl under and take a look...What will I look for? If its broken It
>> will look like? Maybe its pretty self evident..havn't been down there
>> lately. Thanks Thom!
> </pre>


